    {
      "id": "9cb9f600fafe9466b5051292148965efbf005c99",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 229,
        "name": "Bruno Faccini",
        "email": "bfaccini@nvidia.com",
        "username": "bfaccini"
      },
      "date": "2013-04-19 08:36:17.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve\n\n(1 inline comment)\n\nI agree that using a static struct instead of pointer+malloc should fix the problem, but I think you may have fixed this too by keeping old way and protect the critical path between ptlrpc_stop_pinger()/ptlrpc_stop_main() with pinger_mutex :\n\n--- lustre/ptlrpc/pinger.c.orig\t2013-03-13 11:34:00.000000000 +0100\n+++ lustre/ptlrpc/pinger.c.bfi\t2013-04-19 10:33:34.000000000 +0200\n@@ -330,8 +330,10 @@\n                 }\n         }\n \n+\tmutex_lock(&pinger_mutex);\n         thread_set_flags(thread, SVC_STOPPED);\n         cfs_waitq_signal(&thread->t_ctl_waitq);\n+\tmutex_unlock(&pinger_mutex);\n \n         CDEBUG(D_NET, \"pinger thread exiting, process %d\\n\", cfs_curproc_pid());\n         return 0;\n@@ -398,8 +400,10 @@\n         l_wait_event(pinger_thread->t_ctl_waitq,\n                      thread_is_stopped(pinger_thread), &lwi);\n \n+\tmutex_lock(&pinger_mutex);\n         OBD_FREE_PTR(pinger_thread);\n         pinger_thread = NULL;\n+\tmutex_unlock(&pinger_mutex);\n         RETURN(rc);\n }",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "a9f02ec7bd00966dc0e1685e1bdb08a6172d1340",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 301,
        "name": "Dmitry Eremin",
        "email": "dmitry.eremin@intel.com",
        "username": "dmiter",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2013-04-19 11:09:36.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: (1 inline comment)\n\nI don't see the reason to use locks here for this purpose. Moreover I think dynamic allocation is not justified here also. It just complicate implementation.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
